INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (344, 1, '2011-02-26 04:01:25', '2011-02-26 04:01:25', 'Although aniridia is a rare disease, you are not alone. Don’t deal with aniridia all by yourself, help is out there.\r\n<h3><strong><em>Support</em></strong></h3>\r\n<strong></strong>Aniridia is a lifelong disease and you need the help and support from many people – you family who may also in the same condition and can give you useful advice, you friends, you doctors and your genetic counsellors.\r\n<h3><strong><em>Online Community</em></strong></h3>\r\n<strong></strong>You can share your story in our website with many affected others. You can read and contribute to the tips of living with aniridia, such as useful visual aids, available operations and their outcome. We are one big family.\r\n<h3><strong><em>Resources</em></strong></h3>\r\n<strong></strong>Check out our online resources for general information, diagnosis, treatment, and coping strategies. Learn about aniridia related symptoms and get the latest news on clinical advancement.', 'How can I find help?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '262-revision-6', '', '', '2011-02-26 04:01:25', '2011-02-26 04:01:25', '', 262, 'http://web3.cmmt.ubc.ca/dev/uncategorized/262-revision-6/', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (345, 1, '2011-02-26 04:00:47', '2011-02-26 04:00:47', 'Children with aniridia typically have about 20/100 vision, but this varies between individuals. They need to be carefully followed by an ophthalmologist throughout life, so complication can be diagnosed and promptly treated. Vision typically gets worse with age as cataracts progress though these can be treated with surgery and contact lenses. Glaucoma frequently develops and affect the function of optic nerve, further reducing vision. Ongoing screening for Wilm’s tumor is important. With careful treatment and assistance for adapting to living with reduced vision, children with aniridia will have a very good outcome.\r\n\r\nIt has been suggested that gene therapy may improve several of the clinical defects. If the affected individuals are identified by prenatal diagnosis, partial therapeutic correction of the lens is possible by gene therapy.\r\n\r\nMost children with aniridia will have normal intelligence, and it is important to build children’s self-esteem and independence. This is essential for them to fully participate in life activities with low vision that might gradually progress to blindness. Genetic counselling can help parents to learn about the disorder itself and what to be expected in order to cope with the condition.', 'What are some treatments and outcomes?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '260-revision-3', '', '', '2011-02-26 04:00:47', '2011-02-26 04:00:47', '', 260, 'http://web3.cmmt.ubc.ca/dev/uncategorized/260-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (109, 1, '2011-01-10 07:25:28', '2011-01-10 07:25:28', '<h1><span>What is Aniridia?</span></h1>\r\nAniridia is characterized by complete or partial absence of the iris. Pax6, which is responsible for eye development, does not function correctly and disrupt the iris development in the fetus. There are many variations of aniridia that range from mild to severe. Depending on what other conditions affected the eyes, visual acuity may remain relatively unimpaired or greatly reduced.\r\n\r\nAniridia is a very rare disease and seen in 1 of 64,000 -96,000 live births. Since it is inherited as an autosomal-dominant trait, each child born to an affected parent will have a 50% chance of having the gene. However, the expression of the gene may vary within families as well as between families. Affected individuals usually show little variability between the two eyes (bilateral). 2/3of all cases come with a family history. Aniridia also occurs in sporadic form, which means the child does not have a family history of the disease. This counts for 1/3 of cases.\r\n<h1>What other conditions are commonly associated with Aniridia?</h1>\r\nAniridia is a part of Wilms tumor aniridia geniourinary anomalies, and mental retardation (WAGR) syndrome. Deletion involves the PAX6 locus and the adjacent WT1 (Wilms tumor) locus, and one copy of the PAX6 gene is missing in each cell.\r\n\r\nMutation in PAX6 may cause eye problems other than aniridia. Most mutations occur in one of the copy of PAX6 gene and change single protein building blocks (amino acids) in the PAX6 proteins. Since such mutations do not eliminate the protein’s function but reduce their ability to bind to DNA.\r\n\r\nNystagmus (the involuntary eye movement) is the most common associated condition and occurs in nearly 90% of affected children. Cataract (cloudy lens of the eye) occurs in 85% of affected children, and Glaucoma (increased pressure in the eye) occurs in 70% of affected children.\r\n\r\nAniridia can also be in association with aniridic keratopathy (cloudy cornea), fovea or macular hypoplasia (underdevelopment of the retina at the back of the eye),ectopia papillae (pupils not centrally positioned), microphthalmia (small eyes), optic nerve hypoplasia (underdevelopment of the structures that carry information form the eyes to the brain), amblyopia (loss of vision of the weaker eye), microcornea (small cornea), and strabismus (crossing or wandering of the eye).\r\n<h1>What are some treatments and outcomes?</h1>\r\nChildren with aniridia typically have about 20/100 vision, but this varies between individuals. They need to be carefully followed by an ophthalmologist throughout life, so complication can be diagnosed and promptly treated. Vision typically gets worse with age as cataracts progress though these can be treated with surgery and contact lenses. Glaucoma frequently develops and affect the function of optic nerve, further reducing vision. Ongoing screening for Wilm’s tumor is important. With careful treatment and assistance for adapting to living with reduced vision, children with aniridia will have a very good outcome.\r\n\r\nIt has been suggested that gene therapy may improve several of the clinical defects. If the affected individuals are identified by prenatal diagnosis, partial therapeutic correction of the lens is possible by gene therapy.\r\n\r\nMost children with aniridia will have normal intelligence, and it is important to build children’s self-esteem and independence. This is essential for them to fully participate in life activities with low vision that might gradually progress to blindness. Genetic counselling can help parents to learn about the disorder itself and what to be expected in order to cope with the condition.\r\n<div>\r\n<h1>What is the risk for other family members?</h1>\r\n<strong>Isolated aniridia</strong> (occurring in the absence of other systemic involvement): The risk of the siblings of the affected child depends on the parents’ genetic status. If the parent has isolated anirdia or has an identifiable PAX6 mutation, the risk is 50%. If the parents are unaffected, the risk is low. Each child of an individual with isolated aniridia has a 50% chance of inheriting the PAX6 mutation and developing aniridia.\r\n\r\n<strong>WAGR Syndrome: </strong>If a parent has a balanced chromosome rearrangement including the PAX6 locus and the adjacent WT1 locus, the risk to other offspring increases. If the affected child has a de novo contiguous gene deletion and neither parent has evidence of mosaicism for the deletion, the risk for other offspring is no greater than that in the general population.\r\n\r\nIndividuals with WAGR syndrome caused by a cytogenetic deletion generally do not reproduce.\r\n<h1>More about PAX6</h1>\r\nHuman PAX6 is on chromosome 11p13 and encodes a 422 amino acid transcriptional regulator. PAX6 is a transcription factor that is required to regulate genes’ expression, and the specified expression pattern is responsible for proper development. The principal sites of PAX6 expression are the eye, the brain, and spinal cord. Mutations in PAX6 may disrupt this pattern and lead to aniridia phenotype.\r\n\r\nTheses mutations are summarized in The Human PAX6 Mutation Database. Most of them result in pre-mature translational termination (incomplete amino acid sequence) on one of the two gene copies (allele), and haploinsufficiency of the gene has been suggested to cause aniridia. On the other hand, only a few cases of missense mutations (the amino acid sequence has been altered) has been detected. It has also been reported that mutations in neighbouring regions of DNA also cause aniridia by interfering of PAX6 expression. Such mutations lead to a decreased of functional PAX6 proteins.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="365" caption="Human chromosome 11. Reference: http://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/dynamicImages/chromomap/PAX6.jpeg"]<img src="http://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/dynamicImages/chromomap/PAX6.jpeg" alt="" width="365" height="185" />[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="300" caption="Pax 6 protein structure. Reference: http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Structure/mmdb/mmdbimage.fcgi?small=f&amp;id=74869"]<img src="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Structure/mmdb/mmdbimage.fcgi?small=f&amp;id=74869" alt="" width="300" height="300" />[/caption]\r\n<h1>What is haploinsufficiency?</h1>\r\nHaploinsufficiency describes the situation in which an individual is affected although having a copy of the normal gene as well as a copy of mutated gene. The single copy of gene is incapable of producing enough proteins for normal function.\r\n<h1>References:</h1>\r\nLindeke, LL. Aniridia. Minnesota Department of Health Fact Sheet. Nov 2005.\r\n\r\nKokotas H. and Peterson MB. Clinical and molecular aspects of aniridia. Clin Genet 2010: 77: 409-420\r\n\r\nHingorani, M. and Moore, A. Aniridia- Includes: Isolated Aniridia, Wilms Tumor-Aniridia-Genital Anomalies-Retardation (WAGR) Syndrome. GeneReview, 2008.\r\n\r\n</div>', 'About Aniridia', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2-revision-9', '', '', '2011-01-10 07:25:28', '2011-01-10 07:25:28', '', 2, 'http://web3.cmmt.ubc.ca/dev/uncategorized/2-revision-9/', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
