INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (256, 1, '2011-02-24 04:57:42', '2011-02-24 04:57:42', 'Aniridia is a part of Wilms tumor aniridia geniourinary anomalies, and mental retardation (WAGR) syndrome. Deletion involves the PAX6 locus and the adjacent WT1 (Wilms tumor) locus, and one copy of the PAX6 gene is missing in each cell.\r\n\r\nMutation in PAX6 may cause eye problems other than aniridia. Most mutations occur in one of the copy of PAX6 gene and change single protein building blocks (amino acids) in the PAX6 proteins. Since such mutations do not eliminate the protein’s function but reduce their ability to bind to DNA.\r\n\r\nNystagmus (the involuntary eye movement) is the most common associated condition and occurs in nearly 90% of affected children. Cataract (cloudy lens of the eye) occurs in 85% of affected children, and Glaucoma (increased pressure in the eye) occurs in 70% of affected children.\r\n\r\nAniridia can also be in association with aniridic keratopathy (cloudy cornea), fovea or macular hypoplasia (underdevelopment of the retina at the back of the eye),ectopia papillae (pupils not centrally positioned), microphthalmia (small eyes), optic nerve hypoplasia (underdevelopment of the structures that carry information form the eyes to the brain), amblyopia (loss of vision of the weaker eye), microcornea (small cornea), and strabismus (crossing or wandering of the eye).', 'What other conditions are commonly associated with Aniridia?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-other-conditions-are-commonly-associated-with-aniridia', '', '', '2011-02-26 03:59:57', '2011-02-26 03:59:57', '', 0, 'http://web3.cmmt.ubc.ca/dev/?post_type=disease_info&p=256', 0, 'disease_info', '', 0); 
