INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (279, 1, '2011-02-24 09:38:20', '2011-02-24 09:38:20', '<strong>Haploinsufficiency </strong>describes the situation in which an individual is affected although having a copy of the normal gene as well as a copy of mutated gene. The single copy of gene is incapable of producing enough proteins for normal function.', 'What is haploinsufficiency?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '268-autosave', '', '', '2011-02-24 09:38:20', '2011-02-24 09:38:20', '', 268, 'http://web3.cmmt.ubc.ca/dev/uncategorized/268-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (280, 1, '2011-02-24 07:45:28', '2011-02-24 07:45:28', '<img class="alignnone" title="iris" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/65/Eye_iris.jpg" alt="" width="703" height="470" />\r\n\r\nAniridia is characterized by complete or partial absence of the iris. Pax6, which is responsible for eye development, does not function correctly and disrupt the iris development in the fetus. There are many variations of aniridia that range from mild to severe. Depending on what other conditions affected the eyes, visual acuity may remain relatively unimpaired or greatly reduced.\r\n\r\nAniridia is a very rare disease and seen in 1 of 64,000 -96,000 live births. Since it is inherited as an autosomal-dominant trait, each child born to an affected parent will have a 50% chance of having the gene. However, the expression of the gene may vary within families as well as between families. Affected individuals usually show little variability between the two eyes (bilateral). 2/3of all cases come with a family history. Aniridia also occurs in sporadic form, which means the child does not have a family history of the disease. This counts for 1/3 of cases.', 'What is Aniridia?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '251-revision-6', '', '', '2011-02-24 07:45:28', '2011-02-24 07:45:28', '', 251, 'http://web3.cmmt.ubc.ca/dev/uncategorized/251-revision-6/', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (281, 1, '2011-02-24 04:57:42', '2011-02-24 04:57:42', 'Aniridia is a part of Wilms tumor aniridia geniourinary anomalies, and mental retardation (WAGR) syndrome. Deletion involves the PAX6 locus and the adjacent WT1 (Wilms tumor) locus, and one copy of the PAX6 gene is missing in each cell.\r\n\r\nMutation in PAX6 may cause eye problems other than aniridia. Most mutations occur in one of the copy of PAX6 gene and change single protein building blocks (amino acids) in the PAX6 proteins. Since such mutations do not eliminate the protein’s function but reduce their ability to bind to DNA.\r\n\r\nNystagmus (the involuntary eye movement) is the most common associated condition and occurs in nearly 90% of affected children. Cataract (cloudy lens of the eye) occurs in 85% of affected children, and Glaucoma (increased pressure in the eye) occurs in 70% of affected children.\r\n\r\nAniridia can also be in association with aniridic keratopathy (cloudy cornea), fovea or macular hypoplasia (underdevelopment of the retina at the back of the eye),ectopia papillae (pupils not centrally positioned), microphthalmia (small eyes), optic nerve hypoplasia (underdevelopment of the structures that carry information form the eyes to the brain), amblyopia (loss of vision of the weaker eye), microcornea (small cornea), and strabismus (crossing or wandering of the eye).', 'What other conditions are commonly associated with Aniridia?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '256-revision-2', '', '', '2011-02-24 04:57:42', '2011-02-24 04:57:42', '', 256, 'http://web3.cmmt.ubc.ca/dev/uncategorized/256-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
