INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (289, 1, '2011-02-24 04:58:22', '2011-02-24 04:58:22', 'Aniridia is characterized by complete or partial absence of iris and leads to reduced visual acuity and involuntary eye movement in early infancy. Following is some techniques used to identify the ocular abnormalities of aniridia.\r\n<h3><strong><em>Slit lamp examination</em></strong></h3>\r\n<strong></strong>It provides a magnified view of the eye structure and enables anatomical diagnoses in a variety of eye conditions. Partial or complete iris absence and iris translucency may be seen. Cataract and glaucoma can also be detected when present.\r\n<h3><strong><em>Optical coherence tomography (OCT)</em></strong></h3>\r\n<strong></strong>It is a non-invasive technology used for imaging the retina. In atypical cases, OCT can be used to document fovea underdevelopment, but it is difficult to perform in the presence of nystagmus (involuntary eye movement)\r\n<h3><strong><em>High-frequency ultrasound biomicroscopy (UBM)</em></strong></h3>\r\n<strong></strong>Congenital glaucoma can lead to corneal opacity or severe corneal edema (abnormal accumulation of fluid) in infants. UBM can be used to demonstrate iris underdevelopment and/or absence.', 'How is aniridia diagnosed?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '258-revision-2', '', '', '2011-02-24 04:58:22', '2011-02-24 04:58:22', '', 258, 'http://web3.cmmt.ubc.ca/dev/uncategorized/258-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (290, 1, '2011-02-24 04:58:44', '2011-02-24 04:58:44', 'Children with aniridia typically have about 20/100 vision, but this varies between individuals. They need to be carefully followed by an ophthalmologist throughout life, so complication can be diagnosed and promptly treated. Vision typically gets worse with age as cataracts progress though these can be treated with surgery and contact lenses. Glaucoma frequently develops and affect the function of optic nerve, further reducing vision. Ongoing screening for Wilm’s tumor is important. With careful treatment and assistance for adapting to living with reduced vision, children with aniridia will have a very good outcome.\r\n\r\nIt has been suggested that gene therapy may improve several of the clinical defects. If the affected individuals are identified by prenatal diagnosis, partial therapeutic correction of the lens is possible by gene therapy.\r\n\r\nMost children with aniridia will have normal intelligence, and it is important to build children’s self-esteem and independence. This is essential for them to fully participate in life activities with low vision that might gradually progress to blindness. Genetic counselling can help parents to learn about the disorder itself and what to be expected in order to cope with the condition.', 'What are some treatments and outcomes?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '260-revision-2', '', '', '2011-02-24 04:58:44', '2011-02-24 04:58:44', '', 260, 'http://web3.cmmt.ubc.ca/dev/uncategorized/260-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (291, 1, '2011-02-24 04:59:38', '2011-02-24 04:59:38', 'Isolated aniridia (occurring in the absence of other systemic involvement): The risk of the siblings of the affected child depends on the parents’ genetic status. If the parent has isolated anirdia or has an identifiable PAX6 mutation, the risk is 50%. If the parents are unaffected, the risk is low. Each child of an individual with isolated aniridia has a 50% chance of inheriting the PAX6 mutation and developing aniridia.\r\n\r\nWAGR Syndrome: If a parent has a balanced chromosome rearrangement including the PAX6 locus and the adjacent WT1 locus, the risk to other offspring increases. If the affected child has a de novo contiguous gene deletion and neither parent has evidence of mosaicism for the deletion, the risk for other offspring is no greater than that in the general population.\r\n\r\nIndividuals with WAGR syndrome caused by a cytogenetic deletion generally do not reproduce.', 'What is the risk for other family members?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '264-revision-2', '', '', '2011-02-24 04:59:38', '2011-02-24 04:59:38', '', 264, 'http://web3.cmmt.ubc.ca/dev/uncategorized/264-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
